^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|When you respond to a preempt, you have to take many things into account. For example, say partner opens 2@H and you have:|
ht|c|ih|pSK Q 2HK 2DA J 8 7 3CJ T 2|ht|c|at|^j@2
If partner is a sound preemptor, and you are vulnerable (especially at team scoring or opposite a 2nd-seat preempt), you might just bid 4@H.  If partner is a "medium " preemptor, you might bid 2NT to find out if he is minimum or maximum. If he is an aggressive preemptor, you probably should pass. It is so important to know partner's style!|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


ht|h|AT|^b@2
^*B4th seat^*N: In fourth seat, can you open with a preempt (after 3 passes)? Sure. For a 4th seat weak-two, you should have a decent six-card suit and about 10-13 HCP (with less, you would pass the hand out). A 3-level preempt in 4th seat would contain a 7-card suit. After 3 passes, I would open 3@H with something like:|
ht|k|ih|pS2HK Q J T 8 7 3DQ J 9 2C2|ht|k|at|^j@2
(This hand would be too good to open 3@H in any other position.)|
