qx||ht|b|cs|1|cp|4|fp||at|^-{    Comments by Howard Schutzman     }
^-|
CP||fp||at|^b@2
Howard thinks no one should use the rule of 2, 3, and 4 to decide whether or not to preempt. Howard happens to know that Larry Cohen does not use this rule either but simply included it for completeness. This is a very old fashioned rule that is no longer in favor by any experienced player, even those who believe in sound preempts.|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


AT|

As you know,  Howard believes that you should preempt with any hand that is less than an opener and has the right suit length (open a weak 2 with a 6-card suit, a weak 3 with a 7-card suit, and a weak 4 with an 8-card suit), regardless of suit quality. You are protected by the Law of Total Tricks because partner will usually have at least enough length to make the bid follow the Law (and often will have more length). You can be slightly more cautious vulnerable with a bad suit.|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


AT|

Regarding the best time to preempt. Although you definitely should still preempt in 2nd seat, that is the least advantageous seat to preempt. Partner is more likely to have a good hand and you may occasionally preempt partner. But, for you timid preempters, don't use that as an excuse not to preempt! |
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


AT|

In 3rd seat, when you hold a singleton or void, it is often advantageous to preempt one higher than in other seats -- open a weak 2 with a 5-card suit, a weak 3 with a 6-card suit, etc. -This is especially true at favorable vulnerability (you are not vulnerable and the opponents are vulnerable). When you hold a weak hand in 3rd seat, it is a certainty that 4th seat has at least a nice opener, so you want to make it as difficult as you can for the opponents to bid accurately.|
